{"author":{"id":"df79d9acb56ef89cd944cc8548377a5d54d09f0704d032bd86e5f202c0cd02f7"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1536841213,"nonce":"ZcIOu1qpBPTjZuieeX9eOcao5fc=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUzNTk4NzEyMjI=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/2079","origin":"github"},"title":"Non-standard *.loc file entries in kraken","message":"I filed #2077 to fix a quoting error in Kraken, but further work on this area to me points to what looks like a long standing oddity in how the ``kraken_databases.loc`` file entries are used.\n\nThis dates back to https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-devteam/blob/84e3497f464048c6c9b0494205d6d0b7c8082e8d/tool_collections/kraken/tool_data_table_conf.xml.sample \n\n```xml\n\u003c?xml version=\"1.0\"?\u003e\n\u003ctables\u003e\n    \u003c!-- Locations of Kraken database in the required format --\u003e\n    \u003ctable name=\"kraken_databases\" comment_char=\"#\"\u003e\n        \u003ccolumns\u003evalue, name, path\u003c/columns\u003e\n        \u003cfile path=\"tool-data/kraken_databases.loc\" /\u003e\n    \u003c/table\u003e\n\u003c/tables\u003e\n```\n\nThe usual convention here is ``value`` is a DB key, ``name`` is the user-facing description, and ``path`` is the value passed at the command line - usually a filename, folder, or stem depending on the tool. From Kraken I expect this to be the folder name containing files ``database.idx``, ``database.kdb`` and a sub-folder ``taxonomy/``\n\nHowever, this is not what was done for Kraken - looking at the earliest code  \nhttps://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-devteam/blob/2d62edf59196168ad78d64d1cffc5c8f516221fd/tool_collections/kraken/kraken/kraken.xml @davebx did this:\n\n```\nln -s ${kraken_database.fields.path}/${kraken_database.fields.name} \u0026\u0026\nkraken --threads 64 --db ${kraken_database.fields.name}\n...\n```\n\nThere is no test provided, but it evidently assumes ``${kraken_database.fields.name}`` is a folder name within ``${kraken_database.fields.path}``\n\nThis logic persists but is less transparent in the current macro-based code:\n\n```xml\n    \u003ctoken name=\"@INPUT_DATABASE@\"\u003e--db ${kraken_database.fields.name}\u003c/token\u003e\n    \u003ctoken name=\"@SET_DATABASE_PATH@\"\u003eexport KRAKEN_DB_PATH=\"${kraken_database.fields.path}\"\u003c/token\u003e\n```\n\nand in the command:\n\n```\n@SET_DATABASE_PATH@ \u0026\u0026\n...\nkraken\n            --threads \\${GALAXY_SLOTS:-1}\n            @INPUT_DATABASE@\n...\n```\n\nSuggestion:\n\nWe maintain this original behaviour, but support the more typical usage with something along these lines of pseudo code:\n\n```\nif [ -f '${kraken_database.fields.path}/database.kdb ]\n    # Use the path directly\nelif [ -f '${kraken_database.fields.path}/{kraken_database.fields.name}/database.kdb' ]\n    # Backward compatible hack, use path+name\nelse\n    # Raise an error\nend if\n```","files":null}]}